<br>
Interesting indeed. I really hope they do pull it off some day but I'm afraid I'm a bit of a pessimist. I don't think it's a realistic goal. Two hundred million dollars a year! Bloody hell. Thats nearly double Nasa's budget for nuclear spacecraft R&amp;D. What a waste of money. Much as I am in favour of any nuclear research including controlled fusion I think Bush has his priorities mixed up. 2037! More like 3037. Whats worse is that the anti-proliferation brigade uses fusion research as a target. Yales used to attack it because any research of that type can be applied to weaponry and breaches the aims of the CTBT. I don't give a fudge about it myself. I'm all for weapons research. But then I watch Bush telling other nations not to experiment with nuclear weapons programs and I see a bit of hypocrisy. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/03 3:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Controled fusion does exist. It is only a matter of time<br>
before it will become efficient enough to Replace<br>
old fashioned nuclear fission as an energy source for power reactors. I think it will happen long before 2037.<br>
At last report we have achieved the production of<br>
40% of the power input in fusion power generation.<br>
Also atomic rockets will be replaced by fusion rockets in the<br>
future, but the fusion rockets will still need  atomic reactors<br>
to serve as  batteries to provide the energy to ignite the fusion reaction in the fusion reactors/fusion engines.<br>
<br>
